bug.short_desc: Web Hero: Bottom of tab is cut off in Firefox 4

long_desc.thetext:
Created attachment 524554 webhero cutoff screenshot
The full tab isn't visible in Firefox 4 and the bottom part is cut off. Works correctly in Chrome.
Matt, can try to reproduce in 3.6 and IE8/9 please?
William, yes I'm able to reproduce this in Firefox 3.6 IE8 and IE9.

Looks like the font "League Gothic" is used for the broken headings, but it's not defined in an @font-face declaration, so the browser falls back to whatever it can find (Times?).
Two things: - of course the font-face should be properly defined - but if this is the fallback, it's also broken. Should define a reasonable secondary font that doesn't completely break out of bounds.

Adding League Gothic is an easy fix, but finding a fallback that takes the same space is a challenge because League is so narrow. The closest I've found that's still a fairly common installed font is Haettenschweiler, and even that isn't super common. I've added League Gothic in r87119.
But overflow on the body was explicitly hidden in r87072 to eliminate scrollbars, so I don't know that the font alone fixes the cutoff problem. I'm unfamiliar with Facebook tabs so I don't know if scrollbars may be necessary after all.

Correct me if I'm wrong, but I think it's also not possible to define the font size depending on the actually used font? Otherwise you could go for Arial or similar, and just tell it to be smaller than what League would be.

(In reply to comment #4) > Correct me if I'm wrong, but I think it's also not possible to define the font > size depending on the actually used font? Otherwise you could go for Arial or > similar, and just tell it to be smaller than what League would be.
That's exactly the problem. We can't make font-size contingent on font-family, at least not easily. It could possibly be done with JavaScript, but it's not part of CSS. We have to try to find fallback fonts that occupy roughly the same space at the same size.
What I'd love is something like "if (League Gothic) { font-size: 60px; } else { font-size: 40px; }".

Has this been fixed? The page renders correctly in IE8, IE9, and Firefox. I'm no longer able to reproduce the behavior in comment 0 and comment 1.
https://www.facebook.com/pages/Firefox-4/130379370362344?sk=app_176093342441461

(In reply to comment #6) > Has this been fixed? The page renders correctly in IE8, IE9, and Firefox. I'm > no longer able to reproduce the behavior in comment 0 and comment 1. > > https://www.facebook.com/pages/Firefox-4/130379370362344?sk=app_176093342441461
The font problem (which is actually a separate issue) is fixed but I'm still seeing the bottom cut off in Firefox 4 and Opera 10 on Mac. It works for me in Firefox 3.6 on Mac, as well as Safari 5 and Chrome 10 (Mac), and I haven't checked any Windows browsers.
Our page is being displayed in an iframe, the height of which is determined when the page loads. But for some reason Facebook is miscalculating the height as 800px in some browsers and correctly calculating it as 1220px in others.
I can't make sense of the JavaScript but my best guess is that it's something to do with when different load events fire, which may vary between browsers. For example, if their script sets the height when our page's DOM is loaded, Firefox 4's JS engine might be firing that "DOM loaded" event before the CSS has fully been applied so it's not accounting for all the spacing and margins. But Webkit might not fire that event until it has calculated the rendered sizes after CSS, so it gets the correct final height. Only a theory, and I don't know what the best fix would be.
Zach or anyone else, any ideas on a fix for this? We need to get this resolved on Monday. Thanks!

(In reply to comment #7) > Firefox 4's JS engine might be firing that "DOM loaded" event before the CSS > has fully been applied so it's not accounting for all the spacing and margins. > But Webkit might not fire that event until it has calculated the rendered sizes > after CSS, so it gets the correct final height. Only a theory, and I don't know > what the best fix would be.
At first I was wondering if there was a setting for this in the Facebook app's config pages ("minimum size" or something)? I don't have access to this test app, so I can't tell :(
Second, I was wondering, if the JS reads some stuff too early, perhaps it'd help to apply a CSS style of "min-height: 1220px" to the iframe's body or similar?
jlongster is taking a look. Let me know how it goes.

fixed in r87168. I wrapped all the content in a div and applied the min-height to it instead of body.
https://www.facebook.com/pages/Firefox-4/130379370362344?sk=app_176093342441461
Yikes, it's actually happening again now. I guess I didn't fix it.

(In reply to comment #12) > I'm betting it's something to do with this: > > window.fbAsyncInit = function() { > FB.Canvas.setAutoResize(); > } > > I think that's the bit that tells Facebook to measure the page and resize the > frame. Maybe if we just force a delay before that fires? Or wrap it in a > body.onload ?
I tried a few things, but it works to change that function just to FB.Canvas.setSize(). That function is weird; it polls the page which I don't like, and it seems to break things. But setSize() fixed it!
